de with delayed repolarisation","Sodium channel blockade with slow binding kinetics","Sodium channel blockade with rapid binding kinetics","Beta adrenoceptor blockade with reduced automaticity"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EClass 1c antiarrhythmic drugs work through \u003Cstrong\u003Esodium channel blockade with slow binding kinetics\u003C/strong\u003E. This characteristic slow binding and unbinding to sodium channels distinguishes them from other antiarrhythmic classes and results in marked slowing of cardiac conduction velocity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium channel blockade with rapid binding kinetics\u003C/strong\u003E describes class 1b drugs like lignocaine, which have much faster kinetics.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPotassium channel blockade with delayed repolarisation\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of class 3 drugs like amiodarone, which primarily affect repolarisation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta adrenoceptor blockade with reduced automaticity\u003C/strong\u003E describes class 2 drugs like metoprolol, which work through the sympathetic system.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium channel blockade with negative inotropy\u003C/strong\u003E describes class 4 drugs like verapamil, which primarily affect the calcium current.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe slow kinetics of class 1c drugs make them particularly effective at suppressing ectopic beats and re-entrant arrhythmias, though they must be used cautiously in structural heart disease due to their marked conduction slowing effects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Class 1c antiarrhythmic drugs block sodium channels with slow onset and offset kinetics, distinguishing them from class 1b drugs which have fast kinetics.","Unlike class 3 drugs which prolong action potential duration, class 1c drugs have minimal effects on repolarisation.","Class 1c antiarrhythmic drugs markedly slow cardiac conduction velocity compared to other antiarrhythmic classes."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62521"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17113"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62521"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:23:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:30:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9803"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77015"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (id